[normal]6.[bold] [bold]              [bold]What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and [bold]PhD[bold] students in academic careers?[bold]6.1
[normal]              [bold] [bold]Career Support:[bold] Clear career advice should be available which is sensitive to diversity and gender and a clear career structure should be provided detailing what career paths they can take so that they can make an informed decision about their career choice. Improved inf
[normal]ormation and communication on internal jobs, and accessibility to positions is critical, to increase the chances of the graduate/PhD Student remaining at the institution.
[normal]6.2
[normal] [bold]              [bold]PI Support:[bold] Principal Investigators should be better supported to understand and
[normal] deliver mentoring &amp; career advice as this is often the person the graduates look to for support. It is important that PIs are involved with the Researcher Development Team so they are able to offer the graduates all the opportunities open to them. 
[normal]6.3
[normal]              [bold] [bold]N[bold]etworking:[bold] Improve opportunities for networking so graduates/students have the chance to meet early career researchers/lecturers and hear their stories about how they made the transition from student to staff. Cross-faculty and multi-disciplinary events op
[normal]en more doors across the University where they would be able to work based on their expertise in particular fields.  
[normal]6.4
[normal] [bold]              [bold]Role Models:[bold] Showcase and celebrate successful female academics.  Ensure that conferences, seminars and events include female speaker
[normal]s wherever possible.
[normal]6.5
[normal] [bold]              [bold]Communication:[bold] Ensure staff and students are aware of the policies in place to help support women so concerns from students can be answered quickly or found out easily. Running events where women graduates can see/hear that it is 
[normal]possible to be a mother and an academic and highlighting the support available following maternity leave is important. 
[normal]6.6
[normal] [bold]              [bold]Work-life balance:[bold] We need to look at the environment within higher education where the long hours culture still dominates.  If we 
[normal]want to encourage and retain women then we need to do more to support those who want to work part-time, flexibly or take a career break and for there to be opportunities for
[normal] them to progress their career.
[normal] We also need to stop the long-hours culture
[normal] to show
[normal] it 
[normal]is possible to work successfully whil
[normal]st
[normal] retaining a work-life balance.
[normal]6.7
[normal] [bold]              [bold]The University of Manchester supports females who wish to pursue an academic career in the following ways:   [bold]The University 
[normal]h
[normal]as forums and networks for graduates and stud
[normal]ents 
[normal]to share their experiences with each other and staff. There are also
[normal] formal mentoring schemes where students are linked with an experienced member of staff and schemes where students can assist their peers. Other examples of good practice we have to ensure
[normal] that women progress into academic careers
[normal] are listed below in 7
[normal]. 
